    "Californium": `Californium (Cf) is a silvery, radioactive actinide metal. It is one of the most useful synthetic elements due to its strong neutron emission. Key details about Californium (Cf) are as follows:
Uses: Used as a neutron source for neutron activation analysis, in neutron radiography, to start nuclear reactors, in cancer treatment (brachytherapy), and in mining to detect gold and silver ores.
Production/Extraction: Produced by bombarding berkelium with neutrons in high-flux nuclear reactors. Only a few grams are produced worldwide each year. Extremely expensive to produce.
History: Discovered in 1950 by Stanley G. Thompson, Kenneth Street Jr., Albert Ghiorso, and Glenn T. Seaborg at UC Berkeley. Named after California.
Health Effects & Safety: Highly radioactive. Cf-252 is a strong neutron emitter. Extremely dangerous if inhaled or ingested. Requires heavy shielding and remote handling.
Price/Market: Extremely expensive (estimated at $27 million per gram for Cf-252). Available only to licensed facilities. Limited production capacity worldwide.
Properties: Radioactive, silvery metallic appearance, very dense, Cf-252 is a strong spontaneous neutron emitter, most stable isotope Cf-251 has half-life of 898 years, melting point around 900°C.`,

